                    <desc>
                      Scribal intervention:
                      words of text are written interlinearly (<locus target="#16v #23r #41v #43v" facs="019 025 044 046"/>, etc.);
                      words of text are written interlinearly with a symbol (┴) marking the location where the text is to be inserted (<locus target="#31r" facs="033"> f. 31r, line 6</locus>);
                      erasure markings are visible (<locus target="#3r #16v #30r #78r" facs="005 019 032 080"/>, etc.);
                      text has been removed (e.g., <locus target="#14r #20v #130v #144r" facs="016 023 133 146"/>)
                    </desc>
                    </item>
                    <item xml:id="e13">
                    <desc>
                    <locus target="#144r #145v #146r" facs="146 148"/>
                    lines have been drawn above and below text to signal its erasure, often due to repeated text
                    </desc>
                    </item>
                    <item xml:id="e14">
                    <desc>
                      The scribe regularly has to complete a line of text on another line. Much of the problem is addressed through the selection of an appropriate aspect ratio for the codex combined with an appropriate script size. But, where the line of text is still too long, the scribe completes the line of text above or below the end of the line (throughout). This scribe also will reduce the font size at the end of lines to avoid having to go onto the next line (e.g., <locus target="#55v  #56r" facs="058"/>)
                    </desc>
                    </item>
